
1. How do you convert a Bar Chart into a Pie Chart in Google Sheets?

Can't directly convert - Google Sheets requires recreating:

Quick Steps:

    Delete existing bar chart (right-click → Delete)

    Select data range (labels + values)

    Insert → Chart

    Chart type dropdown → Pie chart

Pro Tip: Copy chart style settings first (colors, fonts) from old chart.



2. What is the purpose of the Chart Style option?

Chart Style controls visual appearance:

| What it changes   | Examples           |
| ----------------- | ------------------ |
| Background color  | White, gradient    |
| Font family/size  | Arial 12pt         |
| Chart colors      | Blue/orange scheme |
| Shadow effects    | Drop shadow on     |
| Maximum font size | Auto-adjust labels |



3. When should you use a Pie Chart instead of a Bar Chart?

| Use PIE when                | Use BAR when                |
| --------------------------- | --------------------------- |
| Few categories (≤6 slices)  | Many categories (>6)        |
| Parts of WHOLE (100% total) | Compare values across items |
| Budget allocation           | Sales by month (10+ months) |
| Market share                | Performance ranking         |
| Simple proportions          | Time series data            |

PIE: Website traffic sources (40% Google, 30% Direct...)
BAR: Monthly sales Jan-Dec



4. How can you enable 3D mode for a Pie Chart?

Simple toggle:

    Click chart → Chart editor opens

    Customize tab → Pie chart section

    Check "3D" checkbox ✅

    Slices get depth/shadow effect

Also in:

    Pie slice settings → Individual 3D control

    Chart style → Overall 3D appearance

Note: 3D best for presentations, 2D for data analysis.



5. What type of data is suitable for Pie Charts?

Perfect data structure:

A Column: Labels     B Column: Values
"Google"             450
"Direct"             320  
"Facebook"           180
"Email"              50

Requirements:

    2 columns only (Category + Number)

    Positive numbers (no negatives/zeros)

    Total = 100% (sums to whole)

    ≤8 categories (avoid tiny slices)

    No time series (use line/bar instead)

BAD for Pie:

Monthly sales (12 months) → Use Bar
Negative values           → Impossible
1000 categories           → Unreadable

Pie charts shine with 3-6 meaningful categories showing proportions! 🥧📊
